`crates/steno/src/bin` holds standalone binaries that turn `dict.steno` into every artifact the rest of the system consumes: the two Plover dictionaries (`build_dict.rs`), the Neovim plugin's snippet pair (`build_nvim.rs`), a manual size-comparison report (`measure.rs`), and the tree-browser JSON for `viz/index.html` (`viz_data/`). Depending on this directory means running one of these binaries by name; nothing here is imported as a library — all real logic lives in the `steno` lib crate, and each binary here is orchestration plus its own output format.

All four binaries share the same workspace-root assumption: `root()` (or equivalent) resolves `CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR/../..`, hardcoding that the crate sits two directories below the workspace root containing `dict.steno` and `out/`. Moving the `steno` crate breaks every binary in this directory simultaneously, not just one. All also feed the same `parse_source` → `expand_dict(&entries, None)` pipeline before diverging into their own build/format step, and all collision-check via `BTreeSet`-deduplicated stroke/keyset lists before reporting — a corpus change producing new collisions will surface (with possibly different messages) in `build_dict`, `build_nvim`, and `measure` alike.

`build_dict.rs` and `build_nvim.rs` share a stronger invariant beyond collision-checking: both guard *all* outputs before writing *any* of them, so a failed build never leaves a mismatched stale-plus-fresh file pair on disk. `measure.rs` writes nothing — it's read-only tooling, and its `NOPARAM` stroke table must be hand-kept in sync with `dict.steno`'s current function-shape strokes or measurements silently skew. `viz_data/` is architecturally separate from the other three: it's a whole subdirectory with its own multi-pass pipeline and a hand-coupled JSON contract with `viz/index.html`, rather than a single orchestration file.

Error handling is uniform across the flat binaries: stringly-typed `Result<_, String>`, no panics on expected failure paths, funneled to a `fail()`/stderr/`ExitCode::FAILURE` pattern.